#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:160
#, no-wrap
msgid "Logical Volume Manager (LVM)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:163
#, no-wrap
msgid "**L**ogical **V**olume **M**anager (*LVM*)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:165
#, no-wrap
msgid "The partition created by the **standard partition** cannot dynamically adjust the resources of the hard disk, once the partition is mounted, the capacity is completely fixed, this constraint is unacceptable on the server. Although the standard partition can be forcibly expanded or shrunk through certain technical means, it is easy to cause data loss. LVM can solve this problem very well. LVM is available under Linux from kernel version 2.4, and its main features are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "More flexible disk capacity;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Online data movement;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Disks in _stripe_ mode;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mirrored volumes (recopy);\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:171
#, no-wrap
msgid "Volume snapshots (_snapshot_).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:173
#, no-wrap
msgid "The principle of LVM is very simple: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:177
#, no-wrap
msgid "a logical abstraction layer is added between the physical disk (or disk partition) and the file system\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:177
#, no-wrap
msgid "merge multiple disks (or disk partition) into Volume Group(**VG**) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:177
#, no-wrap
msgid "perform underlying disk management operations on them through something called Logical Volume(**LV**).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:179
#, no-wrap
msgid "**The physical media**: The storage medium of the LVM can be the entire hard disk, disk partition, or RAID array. The device must be converted, or initialized, to an LVM Physical Volume(**PV**), before further operations can be performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:181
#, no-wrap
msgid "**PV(Physical Volume)**: The basic storage logic block of LVM. To create a physical volume, you can use a disk partition or the disk itself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:183
#, no-wrap
msgid "**VG(Volume Group)**: Similar to physical disks in a standard partition, a VG consists of one or more PV.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:185
#, no-wrap
msgid "**LV(Logical Volume)**: Similar to hard disk partitions in standard partitions, LV is built on top of VG. You can set up a file system on LV.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:187
#, no-wrap
msgid "<b><font color=\"blue\">PE</font></b>: The smallest unit of storage that can be allocated in a Physical Volume, default to <b>4MB</b>. You can specify an additional size.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:189
#, no-wrap
msgid "<b><font color=\"blue\">LE</font></b>: The smallest unit of storage that can be allocated in a Logical Volume. In the same VG, PE and LE are the same and correspond one to one.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:191
#, no-wrap
msgid "![Volume group, PE size equal to 4MB](images/07-file-systems-004.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:193
#, no-wrap
msgid "The disadvantage is that if one of the physical volumes becomes out of order, then all the logical volumes that use this physical volume are lost. You will have to use LVM on raid disks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:197
#, no-wrap
msgid "    LVM is only managed by the operating system. Therefore the _BIOS_ needs at least one partition without LVM to boot.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:201
#, no-wrap
msgid "    In the physical disk, the smallest storage unit is the **sector**; in the file system, the smallest storage unit of GNU/Linux is the **block**, which is called **cluster** in Windows operating system.; in RAID, the smallest storage unit is **chunk**.\n"
msgstr ""

