#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:763
#, no-wrap
msgid "Communication files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:766
#, no-wrap
msgid "These are the pipe (_pipes_) and the _socket_ files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:769
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"* **Pipe files** pass information between processes by FIFO (_First In, First Out_).\n"
"One process writes transient information to a _pipe_ file and another reads it. After reading, the information is no longer accessible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:771
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Socket files** allow bidirectional inter-process communication (on local or remote systems). They use an _inode_ of the file system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "Link files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:775
#, no-wrap
msgid "These files give the possibility to give several logical names to the same physical file. A new access point to the file is therefore created.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:777
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are two types of link files:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:780
#, no-wrap
msgid "Soft link file, also called symbolic link files;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:780
#, no-wrap
msgid "Hard link file, also called physical link files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:782
#, no-wrap
msgid "Their main features are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:787
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Link types        | Description        | \n"
"| ---               | ---                |\n"
"| soft link file    | A shortcut similar to Windows. It has permission of 777 and points to the original file. When the original file is deleted, the linked file and the original file are displayed in red.|\n"
"| Hard link file    | The original file has the same _ inode_ number as the hard-linked file. They can be updated synchronously, including the contents of the file and when it was modified. Cannot cross partitions, cannot cross file systems. Cannot be used for directories. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:789
#, no-wrap
msgid "Specific examples are as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:790
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# Permissions and the original file to which they point\n"
"Shell > ls -l /etc/rc.locol\n"
"lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 13 Oct 25 15:41 /etc/rc.local -> rc.d/rc.local\n"
"\n"
"# When deleting the original file. \"-s\" represents the soft link option\n"
"Shell > touch /root/Afile\n"
"Shell > ln -s /root/Afile /root/slink1\n"
"Shell > rm -rf /root/Afile\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:802
#, no-wrap
msgid "![Present the effect](images/07-file-systems-019.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:803
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Shell > cd /home/paul/\n"
"Shell > ls –li letter\n"
"666 –rwxr--r-- 1 root root … letter\n"
"\n"
"# The ln command does not add any options, indicating a hard link\n"
"Shell > ln /home/paul/letter /home/jack/read\n"
"\n"
"# The essence of hard links is the file mapping of the same inode number in different directories.\n"
"Shell > ls –li /home/*/*\n"
"666 –rwxr--r-- 2 root root … letter\n"
"666 –rwxr--r-- 2 root root … read\n"
"\n"
"# If you use a hard link to a directory, you will be prompted:\n"
"Shell > ln  /etc/  /root/etc_hardlink\n"
"ln: /etc: hard link not allowed for directory\n"
msgstr ""

