msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:962
#, no-wrap
msgid "This behavior is defined by the **default mask**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:964
#, no-wrap
msgid "The principle is to remove the value defined by the mask at maximum rights without the execution right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:966
#, no-wrap
msgid "For a directory:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:968
#, no-wrap
msgid "![How the SUID works](images/07-file-systems-017.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:970
#, no-wrap
msgid "For a file, the execution rights are removed:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:972
#, no-wrap
msgid "![Default rights of a file](images/07-file-systems-018.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:976
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `/etc/login.defs` file defines the default UMASK, with a value of **022**. This means that the permission to create a file is 755 (rwxr-xr-x). However, for the sake of security, GNU/Linux does not have **x** permission for newly created files, this restriction applies to root(uid=0) and ordinary users(uid>=1000).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:983
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```bash\n"
"    # root user\n"
"    Shell > touch a.txt\n"
"    Shell > ll\n"
"    -rw-r--r-- 1 root root     0 Oct  8 13:00 a.txt\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:984
#, no-wrap
msgid "`umask` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:987
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `umask` command allows you to display and modify the mask.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:988
#, no-wrap
msgid "umask [option] [mode]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:993
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ umask 033\n"
"$ umask\n"
"0033\n"
"$ umask -S\n"
"u=rwx,g=r,o=r\n"
"$ touch umask_033\n"
"$ ls -la  umask_033\n"
"-rw-r--r-- 1 rockstar rockstar 0 nov.   4 16:44 umask_033\n"
"$ umask 025\n"
"$ umask -S\n"
"u=rwx,g=rx,o=w\n"
"$ touch umask_025\n"
"$ ls -la  umask_025\n"
"-rw-r---w- 1 rockstar rockstar 0 nov.   4 16:44 umask_025\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1013
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option |\tDescription                     |\n"
"|--------|----------------------------------|\n"
"| `-S`   | Symbolic display of file rights. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1017
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `umask` does not affect existing files. `umask -S` displays the file rights (without the execute right) of the files that will be created. So, it is not the display of the mask used to subtract the maximum value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1021
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `umask` modifies the mask until the disconnection.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1025
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `umask` command belongs to bash's built-in commands, so when you use `man umask`, all built-in commands will be displayed. If you only want to view the help of `umask`, you need to use the `help umask` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1027
#, no-wrap
msgid "To keep the value, you have to modify the following profile files：\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1029
#, no-wrap
msgid "For all users:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1032
#, no-wrap
msgid "`/etc/profile`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1032
#, no-wrap
msgid "`/etc/bashrc`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1034
#, no-wrap
msgid "For a particular user:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1036
#, no-wrap
msgid "`~/.bashrc`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/07-file-systems.md:1037
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the above file is written, it actually overrides the **UMASK** parameter of `/etc/login.defs`. If you want to improve the security of the operating system, you can set umask to **027** or **077**.\n"
msgstr ""
